FE-SEM images of GCE, POLY(DA)-GCE, POLY(DA-CS)-GCE, and POLY(DA-CS)-AuNPs-GCE are shown in Figs. 2–4


                        . POLY(DA) electropolymerized directly on GCE in the absence of CS displays a regular dispersion (Fig. 2). If the POLY(DA)-GCE was coated with CS beforehand, an irregular and spongy film can be observed (Fig. 2). The following deposition of Au NPs on the POLY(DA-CS)-GCE results in the formation of an interwoven chain-like structure of POLY(DA-CS)-GCE with regularly morphology (Fig. 3), which providing an efficient interface for the following dispersion of AuNPs. Finally, these results confirmed that the GCE was coated by POLY(DA-CS)-Au NPs-GCE film using layer-by-layer strategy, leading to the change in the surface morphology (highly porous honeycomb-like structure) and activity of the electrode. As mentioned above, the hydroxyl functional groups of POLY(DA) are beneficial to the combination with CS from the electrostatic point of view, since CS dissolved in acid (HCl in the present work) is positively charged. Fig. 3 indicated that, the electrodeposition of Au NPs on the surface of POLY(DA-CS)-Au NPs lead to spongy structures. Also, these results confirm that dispersion of Au NPs on the surface of POLY(DA-CS)-Au NPs was performed successfully. As can be seen, the average particle size of Au NPs are about 35 nm. The POLY(DA-CS)-Au NPs nanocomposites exhibit an interconnected and highly porous honeycomb-like structure, suggesting that the nanocomposites can be promising materials for entrapment of selected drugs. More importantly, excellent dispersion of the Au NPs is clearly observed within the POLY(DA-CS) matrix, indicating that the POLY(DA-CS) nanocomposites prepared via simple and convenient assembly exhibit a well-dispersed status due to the strong interactions, electrostatic attraction and H bondings, between P(DA) and CS. It is important to point out that, pure CS would be dissolved in aqueous solution at pH below 6.3 due to the protonation of its NH2 groups. So in this work pure CS cannot be used to modify GCE individually. However, the strong electrostatic interactions between positively charged CS and negatively charged P(DA) result in the aggregation and subsequent preparation of the P(DA-CS), leading to stable existence of the nanocomposites for dispersion of Au NPs over a wide pH range (4.5–11.0). It should be pointed out extreme acidity (pH < 4.5) or alkalinity (pH > 11.0) can cause the dissociation of the P(DA-CS) owing to the blocked coulomb forces between the two components and the destroyed condensed state of the complex by the increased local charge density. Anyway, the enhanced stability of the P(DA-CS) over the pH range from 4.5 to 11.0 compared with pure CS and P(DA) makes the nanocomposites an ideal substrate for immobilization of noble metal nanoparticle (Au NPs in this case) to be used in the PBS buffer of pH 7.4. All of these results were confirmed by EDS analysis (Fig. 5
                        ).

The effect of pH of the supporting electrolyte was also studied by varying the pH in the range of 2.0–10.0. CV studies on the electro-oxidation of selected drugs at various pH were performed at the POLY(DA-CS)-AuNPs-GCE (Fig. 7
                        ). The optimum pH for each drug is reported on Table 1
                        .
